projectInfo.description:
**CartONG** was commissioned by **Maroni Lab**, an urban experimentation laboratory based in Saint Laurent du Maroni in French Guiana, to accompany it in the animation of participatory mapping workshop with the inhabitants of spontaneous neighborhoods in the White Sands area.


Maroni Lab's mission is to enable every citizen to become an actor in the process of urban transformation of this French city in the heart of the Guiana highlands in the Amazon. The Laboratory promotes the animation of a reflection on the urban in all its dimensions and the implementation of participatory and innovative projects which concern living together, the urban citizenship and the improvement of the living environment.


In preparation for these mapping workshops, we would like to update the map on these neighborhoods. The city is already well mapped, thanks to an import of cadastre data that dates from 2014, but the city is expanding rapidly and many new constructions have appeared since, this is particularly the case in the spontaneous neighborhoods in which we will intervene. The much more recent Maxar imagery allows us to complete the map so that participants can better allocate themselves and to facilitate the collection of field data by residents on OSMand. The completed map will then be used to reflect on the issues and potential of this territory!
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Choice of aerial imagery ============ You will use **Maxar Standard Imagery (Beta)** imagery for this project. --- There is already a lot of OSM data entered for the zone; this will be more of a work of updating the existing data. You should prioritize then the modifications! 2. Habitations ============ * **Be as precise as possible! !** _Zoom in to distinguish buildings. Trace each building as a whole even if it is partly covered by trees on the satellite image._ ##**How ?** *With the web editor ID:* 1. Use the **polygon** tool to trace buildings 2. Once the building has been plotted, go to the menu on the left, look for the category **"Building types"**, then at the top of the list, select **"Building"** (this is the generic type that we can use, because we can not know the more specific use of a building from the aerial imagery alone) 3. Finally, correct the right angles by pressing the **"Q" key** ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With the JOSM editor:* 1. Use the **Draw Nodes** tool to draw buildings or the **buildings_tools** plugin.   2. Trace the building and use the **building = yes** tag 3. Finally, if you use the Draw Nodes tool, remember to correct the angles by pressing the **"Q" key** `Warning: Many buildings are very close but in fact do not touch each other, try to draw them close to each other but without connecting them or sharing nodes with other buildings, roads or contours of residential areas. In the iD web editor, when you press the Alt key, you will prevent the nodes from sticking to each other or attaching themselves to a nearby path to accidentally connect to it.` --- 3. Road Network ============ * **Please plot the most clearly identifiable routes** * **Connect routes to the existing network** whenever is possible. * **Very short segments that do not connect to anything should not be mapped** * **Overflow slightly from your square** so that the person mapping to the next square can easily connect to it. **The classification of roads in developing countries is different from that of developed countries.** The appearance and practicability of roads in developing countries are not always representative of their economic and social role. In OSM, the typology of roads is based on the importance of roads and not on the state of their surface or their visual appearance. The typology proposed in OSM for developing countries is based on a mapping experience on several of these countries, as well as many conversations and discussions, it is more adapted to the context of these countries. ##**For this project we will use the following categories:** * **For roads that connect cities between them choose "Secondary Roads" then "Minor or Unclassified Road"** (highway=unclassified) * **Within a village or residential area use "Secondary Roads" then "Residential Road"** (highway=residential) * **Roads of - of 1m (= path) use "Paths" then "Path not drivable"** (highway=path) Only trace major paths that connect to inhabited places or other roads. ##**How ?** *With the web editor ID:* 1. Use the **line** tool to draw the routes 2. Once you have drawn a route, go to the left menu, find the category that corresponds to the typology of the route or path (see definition above) *With the JOSM editor:* 1. Use the **Draw Nodes** tool to trace roads and paths 2. Draw the route and then use the tag corresponding to the typology of it. **Highway = Unclassified** or **Highway = residential** or **Highway = path** (see definition above) --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain in the database OSM data and visible and reusable by all. Be as specific as possible! **Quality is more important than quantity! ** Remember that mapping requires patience, care and attention.

** If you have any questions, please post them in comment**, our volunteers xould be happy to answer !
